1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,267
On a cold bright morning in the spring of
nineteen seventy-four, on a corn farm in

2
00:00:05,267 --> 00:00:10,079
south Georgia that everyone said was
already dead, a single father knelt at

3
00:00:10,079 --> 00:00:15,021
the edge of an irrigation ditch and
poured his last six hundred forty dollars

4
00:00:15,021 --> 00:00:20,029
into the brown water — two thousand live
tilapia, bucket by bucket, silver and

5
00:00:20,029 --> 00:00:24,711
thrashing and gone. The neighbors
laughed. They laughed for three years —

6
00:00:24,711 --> 00:00:29,132
at the co-op, at the feed store, in the
pews after church — until his

7
00:00:29,132 --> 00:00:34,009
six-year-old son stopped telling the kids
at school what his daddy did for a

8
00:00:34,009 --> 00:00:38,691
living. Four years later, those same men
stood silent at the county grain

9
00:00:38,691 --> 00:00:43,438
elevator, staring at a number chalked
beside the name Boone. A number that

10
00:00:43,438 --> 00:00:48,446
should not have been possible without a
single bag of fertilizer. Not one bag.

11
00:00:48,446 --> 00:00:53,388
[SLOWER] The story of that number does
not begin in a field. It begins with a

12
00:00:53,388 --> 00:00:58,395
thirty-gallon fish tank in a widower's
kitchen — and a promise he never got to

13
00:00:58,395 --> 00:00:58,720
keep.

14
00:00:58,720 --> 00:01:04,265
Harlan Boone was thirty-three years old
that spring, and the farm was a hundred

15
00:01:04,265 --> 00:01:09,596
and eighty acres of tired ground he
carried the way a man carries a coffin —

16
00:01:09,596 --> 00:01:15,283
not because he wanted to, but because it
was his to carry. The corn land near the

17
00:01:15,283 --> 00:01:20,401
Chattahoochee Valley had fed three
generations of Boones, and by March of

18
00:01:20,401 --> 00:01:24,240
nineteen seventy-four it looked ready to
bury a fourth.

19
00:01:24,240 --> 00:01:29,527
The trouble had a name, and the name was
in every paper and on every porch that

20
00:01:29,527 --> 00:01:34,475
year: fertilizer. Anhydrous ammonia had
run about eighty dollars a ton two

21
00:01:34,475 --> 00:01:39,559
springs back. By December it had crossed
a hundred and fifty, and it had not

22
00:01:39,559 --> 00:01:44,982
stopped climbing since — nearly double in
eighteen months, with no ceiling anyone

23
00:01:44,982 --> 00:01:50,133
could see. Men who had farmed through
drought and blight and low prices found

24
00:01:50,133 --> 00:01:55,149
themselves beaten by arithmetic. A man
could stand in the middle of his own

25
00:01:55,149 --> 00:02:00,233
field and lose it to a column of numbers
written in an office he would never

26
00:02:00,233 --> 00:02:00,640
visit.

27
00:02:00,640 --> 00:02:06,086
The letter from the Farmers and Merchants
Bank lay on the kitchen table where it

28
00:02:06,086 --> 00:02:11,533
had lain for four days, its creases gone
soft from folding and unfolding. It was

29
00:02:11,533 --> 00:02:17,186
polite. Banks were always polite. What it
said, underneath the politeness, was that

30
00:02:17,186 --> 00:02:22,632
Harlan Boone had two more seasons. Two
harvests to turn the place around, or the

31
00:02:22,632 --> 00:02:28,009
land his grandfather had cleared with
mules would belong to men in Columbus who

32
00:02:28,009 --> 00:02:30,560
had never once smelled it after rain.

33
00:02:30,560 --> 00:02:36,577
At five-forty in the morning the kitchen
was dark except for one light: the pale

34
00:02:36,577 --> 00:02:42,060
green-gold glow of a thirty-gallon
aquarium humming on the counter by the

35
00:02:42,060 --> 00:02:48,001
window, its front corner chipped white
like a broken tooth. Eli dragged a chair

36
00:02:48,001 --> 00:02:54,170
across the linoleum — a screech of wood,
then quiet — and climbed up in his pajama

37
00:02:54,170 --> 00:02:59,729
bottoms, five years old and serious as a
deacon. He pinched the flakes and

38
00:02:59,729 --> 00:03:05,746
scattered them across the water the way
his mother used to. Exactly the way. The

39
00:03:05,746 --> 00:03:08,640
same small, careful turn of the wrist.

40
00:03:08,640 --> 00:03:10,480
"They were hungry," he said.

41
00:03:10,480 --> 00:03:12,960
"I expect they were," Harlan said.

42
00:03:12,960 --> 00:03:18,708
Annie had been gone two years, and nobody
in that kitchen said so. The grief lived

43
00:03:18,708 --> 00:03:24,384
in the house like the smell of coffee —
everywhere, ordinary, breathed in without

44
00:03:24,384 --> 00:03:29,990
noticing. Harlan drank his cup standing
up, watching his son watch the fish, and

45
00:03:29,990 --> 00:03:35,383
did not know that the answer to the
letter on the table had been swimming six

46
00:03:35,383 --> 00:03:40,989
feet away from it all along. He fed that
answer every morning. He simply had not

47
00:03:40,989 --> 00:03:41,840
seen it yet.

48
00:03:41,840 --> 00:03:46,188
[SOFTER] If you have ever been laughed at
for fixing things your own way, this

49
00:03:46,188 --> 00:03:50,480
story was written for you — tell me where
in the world you are watching from.

50
00:03:50,480 --> 00:03:56,250
Sleep quit him around two that night, the
way it sometimes did, without reason and

51
00:03:56,250 --> 00:04:01,877
without apology, and Harlan had learned
not to argue with it. He came downstairs

52
00:04:01,877 --> 00:04:07,647
in his socks and stood in the aquarium's
green light, and because his hands needed

53
00:04:07,647 --> 00:04:13,131
a job, he did the chore that had been
hers. Five gallons out, five gallons in.

54
00:04:13,131 --> 00:04:18,759
Annie had done it every Saturday for nine
years; he had let it slide to whenever

55
00:04:18,759 --> 00:04:24,243
the glass went cloudy. The siphon gurgled
in the quiet. The bucket filled with

56
00:04:24,243 --> 00:04:27,520
water that smelled faintly of pond and
pennies.

57
00:04:27,520 --> 00:04:32,831
He carried it out the back door to dump
it where she always had — the tomato

58
00:04:32,831 --> 00:04:38,354
patch by the porch steps. The night was
cool, the grass wet against his ankles,

59
00:04:38,354 --> 00:04:42,320
the frogs loud down in the bottoms. He
tipped the bucket.

60
00:04:42,320 --> 00:04:46,400
Then he stood there and did not move for
a long time.

61
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:52,145
Two years of neglect. Two years of nobody
weeding, nobody watering, nobody doing

62
00:04:52,145 --> 00:04:57,600
one deliberate thing for that little
square of ground — and it was still the

63
00:04:57,600 --> 00:05:03,055
greenest place on the whole hundred and
eighty acres. The volunteer tomatoes

64
00:05:03,055 --> 00:05:08,800
stood thick as a hedge. Even in the dark
he could smell the difference: the fat,

65
00:05:08,800 --> 00:05:14,400
black smell of soil that was alive, six
steps from fields that were only dirt.

66
00:05:14,400 --> 00:05:20,260
She had been a biology teacher. She
explained things whether or not anyone

67
00:05:20,260 --> 00:05:26,522
asked. "Fish water is not dirty water,"
she used to say, schoolteacher-patient,

68
00:05:26,522 --> 00:05:31,981
hauling this same bucket. "It is
fertilizer that happens to have fish

69
00:05:31,981 --> 00:05:38,083
living in it." She called the tank her
farm the size of a breadbox — the fish

70
00:05:38,083 --> 00:05:44,344
fed the water, the water fed the roots,
and nothing was wasted but her Saturday

71
00:05:44,344 --> 00:05:50,526
mornings. And once, standing at this very
door, she had looked out at the dark

72
00:05:50,526 --> 00:05:56,868
fields and said, "Someday we ought to try
it big." He had said all right. He had

73
00:05:56,868 --> 00:06:00,320
meant it. [PAUSE] Then the somedays ran
out.

74
00:06:00,320 --> 00:06:05,040
In the morning Eli stood on his chair
with his nose an inch from the glass.

75
00:06:05,040 --> 00:06:07,360
"How come Mom's plants never died?".

76
00:06:07,360 --> 00:06:10,160
Harlan went still with the coffee pot in
his hand.

77
00:06:10,160 --> 00:06:11,360
"Say that again.".

78
00:06:11,360 --> 00:06:17,360
"Mom's tomatoes. Everything else on the
farm dies. How come hers never do?".

79
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:23,967
[SLOWER] The idea did not strike him. It
was nothing like lightning. It came the

80
00:06:23,967 --> 00:06:30,073
way water comes through a cracked
foundation — quiet, patient, finding the

81
00:06:30,073 --> 00:06:36,513
low places, already inside before a man
thinks to look. By the time he set the

82
00:06:36,513 --> 00:06:39,440
coffee pot down, it was everywhere.

83
00:06:39,440 --> 00:06:44,905
There was one thing Harlan Boone knew
that no other farmer in the county knew,

84
00:06:44,905 --> 00:06:49,873
and he had spent six years in the
Mississippi Delta learning it: how to

85
00:06:49,873 --> 00:06:55,409
keep fish alive in water that did not
particularly want them. Grow-out ponds at

86
00:06:55,409 --> 00:07:00,874
a catfish hatchery outside Belzoni —
feeding schedules, oxygen crashes at four

87
00:07:00,874 --> 00:07:06,339
in the morning, the exact shade of green
a pond turns two days before it kills

88
00:07:06,339 --> 00:07:12,158
everything in it. When his father's heart
gave out, he had come home and folded all

89
00:07:12,158 --> 00:07:15,920
of that knowledge away like a uniform
from an old war.

90
00:07:15,920 --> 00:07:21,632
That night he called Ray, long-distance,
leaning against the wall by the icebox,

91
00:07:21,632 --> 00:07:23,440
the cord stretched tight.

92
00:07:23,440 --> 00:07:28,783
Ray listened, whistled softly, and then
laughed like tearing paper. "Not

93
00:07:28,783 --> 00:07:34,427
catfish," he said. "Catfish are prima
donnas. What you want is tilapia. They

94
00:07:34,427 --> 00:07:39,920
breed like a rumor, they eat anything
that holds still, and they thrive in

95
00:07:39,920 --> 00:07:45,639
water a catfish would take to court. A
warm ditch in Georgia? They will think

96
00:07:45,639 --> 00:07:47,520
they never left Africa.".

97
00:07:47,520 --> 00:07:48,480
"How much?".

98
00:07:48,480 --> 00:07:54,804
"Fingerlings run cheap. Two thousand
would cost you about what a used truck

99
00:07:54,804 --> 00:07:56,000
engine does.".

100
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:01,357
It cost him six hundred forty dollars —
every folded bill in the coffee can on

101
00:08:01,357 --> 00:08:06,643
the top shelf, the last money on the
place that the bank did not already have

102
00:08:06,643 --> 00:08:12,209
a name for. He bought one more thing: a
small used electric pump off a dairy that

103
00:08:12,209 --> 00:08:16,800
was going under. It was not for
irrigation. It was for circulation.

104
00:08:16,800 --> 00:08:22,542
They released the fish on a bright, cold
Saturday in April, father and son at the

105
00:08:22,542 --> 00:08:27,854
headgates, the ditches running slow and
brown. Bucket by bucket — forty-one

106
00:08:27,854 --> 00:08:33,381
buckets — silver bodies flashing once in
the light and vanishing into the murk

107
00:08:33,381 --> 00:08:39,052
like coins dropped down a well. Eli knelt
at the edge with his sleeves soaked to

108
00:08:39,052 --> 00:08:44,723
the elbow, and when the biggest one held
steady against the current, a hand-long

109
00:08:44,723 --> 00:08:48,240
fish with a torn fin, facing upstream, he
pointed.

110
00:08:48,240 --> 00:08:51,600
"That one's General," he said. "He's in
charge.".

111
00:08:51,600 --> 00:08:54,400
"Then he had better get to work," Harlan
said.

112
00:08:54,400 --> 00:09:00,582
Across the fence line, Earl Dobbins's
tractor slowed, and then it stopped. Earl

113
00:09:00,582 --> 00:09:06,842
sat high on the seat for a long while,
watching a man plant fish in a cornfield.

114
00:09:06,842 --> 00:09:13,182
He took off his cap, wiped his forehead,
put it back on, and drove away without a

115
00:09:13,182 --> 00:09:19,285
word. [WEIGHT] The quiet went with him
down the road. It would not stay quiet.

116
00:09:19,285 --> 00:09:25,466
What Earl carried off that morning was
the first drop against the tin roof. The

117
00:09:25,466 --> 00:09:28,240
sky behind it was three years deep.

118
00:09:28,240 --> 00:09:33,469
The story moved through the county the
way water moves downhill, finding every

119
00:09:33,469 --> 00:09:38,834
low place on its own. At the feed store,
men leaned against pallets of seed corn

120
00:09:38,834 --> 00:09:44,199
and traded it back and forth like a coin
worth spending twice. "Boone's planting

121
00:09:44,199 --> 00:09:49,361
fish now," one of them said, and the
sentence did the work of an entire joke.

122
00:09:49,361 --> 00:09:54,386
At the diner, over coffee cooling in
thick white cups, they improved on it.

123
00:09:54,386 --> 00:09:59,547
Fish instead of fertilizer. A hatchery
man playing at corn. Somebody said the

124
00:09:59,547 --> 00:10:04,980
catfish would come up between the rows by
July, and the booth shook with laughter

125
00:10:04,980 --> 00:10:08,240
that smelled of bacon grease and
cigarette smoke.

126
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:12,560
The sharpest cut did not land on Harlan.
It landed lower.

127
00:10:12,560 --> 00:10:17,228
That fall, in a first-grade classroom
that smelled of paste and pencil

128
00:10:17,228 --> 00:10:22,775
shavings, a boy turned around in his seat
and said, "Your daddy plants fish instead

129
00:10:22,775 --> 00:10:27,646
of corn." The class laughed the way
children laugh — all at once, without

130
00:10:27,646 --> 00:10:32,990
malice and without mercy, which is worse.
Eli came home with his eyes rimmed red

131
00:10:32,990 --> 00:10:38,063
and said nothing. He fed his mother's
aquarium, watched the small fish drift

132
00:10:38,063 --> 00:10:43,475
through their lit world, and went out to
sit on the porch alone. He fed the ditch

133
00:10:43,475 --> 00:10:48,887
fish too, down by the barn, but for the
first morning since spring he did not say

134
00:10:48,887 --> 00:10:50,240
one word to General.

135
00:10:50,240 --> 00:10:56,640
Harlan learned of it two days later, from
the teacher, not from the boy. He never

136
00:10:56,640 --> 00:10:58,320
asked Eli to tell it.

137
00:10:58,320 --> 00:11:03,932
At dusk he came out and sat down on the
porch step beside his son. Cicadas ran

138
00:11:03,932 --> 00:11:09,764
their long saw through the pines, and the
first cool of September was lifting off

139
00:11:09,764 --> 00:11:14,720
the dirt. He did not say they were wrong.
He promised nothing at all.

140
00:11:14,720 --> 00:11:21,028
"Those men laughing," he said. "Not one
of them has ever walked out and looked at

141
00:11:21,028 --> 00:11:25,444
what he's laughing at. [PAUSE] You have.
Every morning.".

142
00:11:25,444 --> 00:11:30,670
Eli leaned into his father's side, small
and warm against him, and the two of them

143
00:11:30,670 --> 00:11:33,444
sat watching the light go out of the
fields.

144
00:11:33,444 --> 00:11:38,969
[SOFTER] Have you ever had to explain to
a child why grown men laugh at the person

145
00:11:38,969 --> 00:11:39,924
he loves most?

146
00:11:39,924 --> 00:11:44,789
Down where the farm road met the county
blacktop, headlights swung through their

147
00:11:44,789 --> 00:11:48,484
own rising dust. A vehicle,
government-white, was turning in.

148
00:11:48,484 --> 00:11:53,285
Mr. Pruitt stepped out of the county
truck with his clipboard already in hand,

149
00:11:53,285 --> 00:11:58,085
as though he had been filling it out on
the drive over. He wore his university

150
00:11:58,085 --> 00:12:03,197
degree the way other men wore a hat — you
could not quite see it, but he never once

151
00:12:03,197 --> 00:12:06,564
took it off. Behind him the engine ticked
as it cooled.

152
00:12:06,564 --> 00:12:12,771
"Mr. Boone," he said. "I thought we might
walk your ditches together. Educationally

153
00:12:12,771 --> 00:12:13,604
speaking.".

154
00:12:13,604 --> 00:12:18,503
They walked the main ditch, Pruitt
setting a slow, patient pace, his voice

155
00:12:18,503 --> 00:12:23,603
pitched at the register a man reserves
for a bright but stubborn child. "Corn

156
00:12:23,603 --> 00:12:28,904
wants about a hundred and twenty pounds
of nitrogen to the acre," he said. "That

157
00:12:28,904 --> 00:12:34,273
is not my opinion. That is the state of
Georgia talking. And this ground of yours

158
00:12:34,273 --> 00:12:39,373
is spent — I have soil tests going back
to your father's day. What a few fish

159
00:12:39,373 --> 00:12:44,742
leave behind in a ditch is a decimal so
small the science doesn't bother to round

160
00:12:44,742 --> 00:12:48,164
it." His pen tapped the clipboard twice,
gavel-soft.

161
00:12:48,164 --> 00:12:53,811
At the headgate he stopped. "And I will
tell you something true, since nobody

162
00:12:53,811 --> 00:12:59,310
else will. Tilapia are not native, Mr.
Boone. Turn an African fish loose in

163
00:12:59,310 --> 00:13:05,106
Georgia water and you are being reckless
with more than your own dirt." On that

164
00:13:05,106 --> 00:13:08,004
point he was right, and Harlan knew it.

165
00:13:08,004 --> 00:13:13,250
Harlan knelt and laid his hand flat on
the galvanized screen bolted across the

166
00:13:13,250 --> 00:13:18,427
headgate, cool and wet under his palm.
"Screens on every gate," he said. "And

167
00:13:18,427 --> 00:13:23,401
winter handles the rest. Water drops
below fifty degrees, tilapia start to

168
00:13:23,401 --> 00:13:27,284
die. [WEIGHT] They can't own a river they
can't survive.".

169
00:13:27,284 --> 00:13:32,533
Pruitt laughed then. One short, unkind
note — a laugh produced rather than felt,

170
00:13:32,533 --> 00:13:37,782
the kind that costs the man who spends it
more than he knows. Of everything that

171
00:13:37,782 --> 00:13:42,964
happened in that ditch, the laugh was
what the years would keep. He wrote three

172
00:13:42,964 --> 00:13:46,884
brisk lines on his clipboard and left
without shaking hands.

173
00:13:46,884 --> 00:13:52,346
That winter he read those three lines
aloud at the January county meeting, as a

174
00:13:52,346 --> 00:13:57,669
cautionary tale about desperation, and
the room laughed exactly on cue, right

175
00:13:57,669 --> 00:14:03,341
where his pause invited it to. Harlan was
not there to hear it. He was home in the

176
00:14:03,341 --> 00:14:08,804
dark, cracking ice off a pump intake by
lantern light, his breath hanging white

177
00:14:08,804 --> 00:14:09,924
above the water.

178
00:14:09,924 --> 00:14:15,399
What Pruitt did not read aloud was the
fourth line, the one he had added in the

179
00:14:15,399 --> 00:14:20,734
truck before pulling away: insolvent by
August. That sentence would take four

180
00:14:20,734 --> 00:14:24,244
years to travel back and find the man who
wrote it.

181
00:14:24,244 --> 00:14:30,238
Spring came in wet and green, and with it
came a company car, waxed to a shine that

182
00:14:30,238 --> 00:14:35,794
had no business on a dirt road. Dale
Kessler stepped out carefully, the way a

183
00:14:35,794 --> 00:14:40,985
man steps onto ice. His shoes were
polished, city-thin, and the red dust

184
00:14:40,985 --> 00:14:45,444
began filming over the leather before he
had crossed the yard.

185
00:14:45,444 --> 00:14:51,566
He did not mock. That was the first thing
Harlan noticed. He offered his hand and

186
00:14:51,566 --> 00:14:57,687
his condolences in the same easy motion.
"I heard about your wife," he said. "Two

187
00:14:57,687 --> 00:15:03,733
years now, is it. A man doesn't get over
a thing like that. He just learns where

188
00:15:03,733 --> 00:15:04,804
to carry it.".

189
00:15:04,804 --> 00:15:09,970
Then the offer, laid out flat and
reasonable on the warm hood of the car: a

190
00:15:09,970 --> 00:15:15,625
full season of nitrogen blend, delivered
and spread, not one dollar owed until the

191
00:15:15,625 --> 00:15:21,210
corn was in and sold. "You're not signing
your life away," Kessler said, smiling.

192
00:15:21,210 --> 00:15:23,444
"You're renting one good year.".

193
00:15:23,444 --> 00:15:28,871
Then he looked past Harlan toward the
house, where Eli's bicycle lay on its

194
00:15:28,871 --> 00:15:34,077
side in the yard, one pedal turned up,
waiting. His voice went soft as a

195
00:15:34,077 --> 00:15:34,884
preacher's.

196
00:15:34,884 --> 00:15:36,164
"Think about the boy.".

197
00:15:36,164 --> 00:15:42,389
And for a moment it sounded reasonable.
It sounded like rain after a dry month —

198
00:15:42,389 --> 00:15:48,063
a guaranteed crop, a certain autumn, all
of it standing there smelling of

199
00:15:48,063 --> 00:15:54,130
aftershave and new upholstery and asking
for nothing until later. Later is the

200
00:15:54,130 --> 00:15:59,725
cheapest word a salesman owns. Harlan
felt the weight of it, and did not

201
00:15:59,725 --> 00:16:02,404
pretend to himself that he didn't.

202
00:16:02,404 --> 00:16:07,524
He looked at his fields, not at Kessler.
He looked for a long time.

203
00:16:07,524 --> 00:16:12,913
"Borrowed money is a rope," he said at
last. "And the man who lends it measures

204
00:16:12,913 --> 00:16:16,644
it to fit your neck before he ever hands
you the end.".

205
00:16:16,644 --> 00:16:22,210
Kessler's smile tightened at the corners,
like something drying. He opened the car

206
00:16:22,210 --> 00:16:27,708
door and spoke over the top of it. "There
is a right way to farm and a wrong way,

207
00:16:27,708 --> 00:16:32,724
Mr. Boone. Come August, one of us gets to
say I told you so. I can wait.".

208
00:16:32,724 --> 00:16:38,282
The car eased away down the road, gravel
popping soft under the tires. In the dust

209
00:16:38,282 --> 00:16:43,497
where he had stood, the prints of those
polished shoes kept their sharp edges

210
00:16:43,497 --> 00:16:48,643
until evening — two neat city shapes
pressed into Georgia dirt, both of them

211
00:16:48,643 --> 00:16:49,604
pointing away.

212
00:16:49,604 --> 00:16:55,174
On June evenings, after the supper dishes
were done, the two of them walked out to

213
00:16:55,174 --> 00:17:00,743
the ditch bank with a coffee can of feed,
and the water came alive at the sound of

214
00:17:00,743 --> 00:17:06,038
their boots — a hundred small mouths
dimpling the surface, dark backs catching

215
00:17:06,038 --> 00:17:11,539
the last light like wet pennies. The air
smelled of mud and warm green water, and

216
00:17:11,539 --> 00:17:14,564
the cicadas were just tuning up in the
pines.

217
00:17:14,564 --> 00:17:19,444
"Where does it go?" Eli asked, watching a
pellet vanish. "After they eat it?".

218
00:17:19,444 --> 00:17:25,030
"Out the other end," Harlan said, and let
the boy finish laughing before he went

219
00:17:25,030 --> 00:17:30,050
on. "Fish waste is ammonia. Near enough
the same thing that comes in Mr.

220
00:17:30,050 --> 00:17:35,706
Kessler's tank trucks. But raw like that,
it burns roots. The water has to change

221
00:17:35,706 --> 00:17:36,484
it first.".

222
00:17:36,484 --> 00:17:37,604
"Change it how?".

223
00:17:37,604 --> 00:17:43,284
"Little living things too small to see."
He cupped a handful of ditch water and

224
00:17:43,284 --> 00:17:48,746
let it run out between his fingers. "One
kind eats ammonia and turns it into

225
00:17:48,746 --> 00:17:54,208
nitrite. Another kind eats nitrite and
turns it into nitrate. And nitrate is

226
00:17:54,208 --> 00:18:00,033
what a root drinks. Your mother taught it
to ninth graders with a fish tank and a

227
00:18:00,033 --> 00:18:05,641
bean sprout." He could still see her
chalkboard — the looping arrows from fish

228
00:18:05,641 --> 00:18:10,884
to plant and back, chalk dust ghosting
the sleeve of her good blue dress.

229
00:18:10,884 --> 00:18:16,292
"But those little things only live in
moving water. Still water goes sour. No

230
00:18:16,292 --> 00:18:21,984
air in it, and everything smothers." He
nodded down the field, to where the small

231
00:18:21,984 --> 00:18:27,321
pump muttered its steady two-beat note in
the dusk. "Way I see it now, these

232
00:18:27,321 --> 00:18:33,085
ditches are this farm's veins. That pump
is its heartbeat. Water that quits moving

233
00:18:33,085 --> 00:18:38,564
is blood that has stopped — and nothing
lives downstream of a stopped heart.".

234
00:18:38,564 --> 00:18:44,039
The fish themselves asked for almost
nothing. The moving water grew algae and

235
00:18:44,039 --> 00:18:49,082
duckweed in the sun, and the tilapia
grazed it like slow green pasture,

236
00:18:49,082 --> 00:18:53,044
turning daylight into fertilizer one
mouthful at a time.

237
00:18:53,044 --> 00:18:59,313
Eli tipped the last of the can into the
ditch. "Mom's fish made her tomatoes

238
00:18:59,313 --> 00:19:04,244
happy," he said. "Yours will make the
corn happy." [SOFTER].

239
00:19:04,244 --> 00:19:12,564
Harlan did not answer that. Some true
things a man just lets stand.

240
00:19:12,564 --> 00:19:17,236
The experts had measured what the water
carried. Nobody had measured what the

241
00:19:17,236 --> 00:19:18,404
water was becoming.

242
00:19:18,404 --> 00:19:23,656
The freeze came in the second week of
January, riding a wind that smelled of

243
00:19:23,656 --> 00:19:28,907
iron, and by morning the thermometer on
the barn wall read nineteen degrees.

244
00:19:28,907 --> 00:19:33,879
Harlan knew before he reached the
ditches. He knew from the silence — no

245
00:19:33,879 --> 00:19:39,341
soft roil of water at the pump outfall,
only the thin creak of ice. The tilapia

246
00:19:39,341 --> 00:19:44,872
floated pale as peeled apples, hundreds
of them, belly-up along the veins of the

247
00:19:44,872 --> 00:19:49,844
farm, exactly as Pruitt had said they
would. Still water, stopped blood.

248
00:19:49,844 --> 00:19:56,065
Eli found General near the culvert, stiff
and gray, long as a man's forearm. He did

249
00:19:56,065 --> 00:20:01,831
not cry loudly. He stood with his boots
in the frost and his breath coming in

250
00:20:01,831 --> 00:20:06,004
small white clouds, and he asked if they
could bury him.

251
00:20:06,004 --> 00:20:10,564
They did. Two shovels, one of them
child-sized, and a cigar box Harlan

252
00:20:10,564 --> 00:20:15,719
emptied of receipts to carry him out to
the pecan tree. There were no speeches.

253
00:20:15,719 --> 00:20:20,741
The frozen ground took an hour to open,
and Eli patted the dirt flat with his

254
00:20:20,741 --> 00:20:25,434
mittens the way a person smooths a
blanket over someone sleeping. Harlan

255
00:20:25,434 --> 00:20:30,787
stood a while looking at the small mound,
then at the house, at the kitchen window

256
00:20:30,787 --> 00:20:35,941
where a fluorescent light burned over a
thirty-gallon tank with a chipped front

257
00:20:35,941 --> 00:20:36,404
corner.

258
00:20:36,404 --> 00:20:42,711
He sat down on the ditch bank, on ground
hard as a church pew, and stayed there

259
00:20:42,711 --> 00:20:43,924
long past noon.

260
00:20:43,924 --> 00:20:50,172
[SLOWER] What finally stood up was not
the farmer. It was the hatchery man. Six

261
00:20:50,172 --> 00:20:56,579
years on the Delta ponds had taught him
that a dead fish is not an ending; a dead

262
00:20:56,579 --> 00:21:02,907
fish is nitrogen and phosphorus, a body
returning what it borrowed. There was an

263
00:21:02,907 --> 00:21:09,315
old story — old as planting itself, the
kind schoolteachers told and nobody could

264
00:21:09,315 --> 00:21:15,322
footnote — of native growers laying a
fish beneath the seed corn so the corn

265
00:21:15,322 --> 00:21:21,890
would want for nothing. Annie had told it
once, at this same table, with chalk dust

266
00:21:21,890 --> 00:21:28,458
still on her sleeve. That week he hitched
the middle-buster and ploughed the winter

267
00:21:28,458 --> 00:21:34,625
kill into his fields, furrow by furrow,
hundreds of silver bodies turned under

268
00:21:34,625 --> 00:21:41,113
the black dirt. The brood stock rode out
the cold in the deep sump pond behind the

269
00:21:41,113 --> 00:21:46,960
barn, and in Annie's aquarium on the
counter, circling beneath the humming

270
00:21:46,960 --> 00:21:50,324
light. Spring would be restocked from
eggs.

271
00:21:50,324 --> 00:21:55,435
The county heard the fish had died and
considered the matter settled. [WEIGHT]

272
00:21:55,435 --> 00:22:00,015
The soil, working slowly in the dark
beneath the frost line, had heard

273
00:22:00,015 --> 00:22:01,608
something else entirely.

274
00:22:01,608 --> 00:22:07,080
Restocking became a rite of the thaw.
Each March, when the sump pond lost its

275
00:22:07,080 --> 00:22:12,480
skin of ice, Harlan and Eli waded the
shallows with dip nets and five-gallon

276
00:22:12,480 --> 00:22:17,952
buckets, carrying survivors and egg
clutches out to the ditches the way other

277
00:22:17,952 --> 00:22:23,784
families carried flats of seedlings. Eli
kept count out loud. He was seldom right,

278
00:22:23,784 --> 00:22:25,368
and never off by much.

279
00:22:25,368 --> 00:22:31,277
What fed them, plainly, was Ray. Twice a
season Harlan drove fingerlings and

280
00:22:31,277 --> 00:22:37,580
gravel-colored egg clutches up to Ray's
hatchery in coolers of aerated water, and

281
00:22:37,580 --> 00:22:43,253
came home with folding money — never
much, but enough for the light bill,

282
00:22:43,253 --> 00:22:49,398
diesel, school shoes. The corn paid for
almost nothing in those years. The fish

283
00:22:49,398 --> 00:22:51,368
paid for everything else.

284
00:22:51,368 --> 00:22:56,820
The changes came small, and they came in
order. First the water: by the summer of

285
00:22:56,820 --> 00:23:02,067
seventy-five the ditches had gone from
mud-brown to a clarity with green light

286
00:23:02,067 --> 00:23:07,655
in it, so that a man standing on the bank
could watch his own shadow swim. Then the

287
00:23:07,655 --> 00:23:12,698
smell: the sour, held-breath stink of
stagnation gave way to the smell of a

288
00:23:12,698 --> 00:23:17,741
healthy pond, weedy and faintly sweet,
the smell Harlan remembered from the

289
00:23:17,741 --> 00:23:23,057
Delta. Then, in October, Eli turned a
spade of dirt by the east ditch and found

290
00:23:23,057 --> 00:23:28,441
an earthworm — the first either of them
had seen on that ground — and carried it

291
00:23:28,441 --> 00:23:33,552
to the house cupped in two hands like a
coin. That same fall a heron took up

292
00:23:33,552 --> 00:23:38,527
fishing the middle ditch, patient and
gray and larcenous; it was the first

293
00:23:38,527 --> 00:23:43,774
thief the farm had attracted in years.
Below all of it, unseen, the corn roots

294
00:23:43,774 --> 00:23:46,568
went down after the water and kept going.

295
00:23:46,568 --> 00:23:51,618
There was one bad night. A second letter
from the bank came in February of

296
00:23:51,618 --> 00:23:57,015
seventy-six, and at two in the morning
Harlan sat at the kitchen table with the

297
00:23:57,015 --> 00:24:02,619
letter open and a pen beside it, the only
sounds in the house the refrigerator and

298
00:24:02,619 --> 00:24:07,669
the low hum of the aquarium light.
[SLOWER] He watched the fish circle the

299
00:24:07,669 --> 00:24:13,135
tank with the chipped corner, around and
around, the way water moves when a pump

300
00:24:13,135 --> 00:24:16,248
keeps faith with it. He did not sign
anything.

301
00:24:16,248 --> 00:24:20,770
In April he boxed a soil sample from the
east forty and mailed it to the state

302
00:24:20,770 --> 00:24:25,233
university, and on the return label he
printed his own name and route number,

303
00:24:25,233 --> 00:24:26,408
plain and unashamed.

304
00:24:26,408 --> 00:24:31,427
The envelope from the state university
came the first week of October, nineteen

305
00:24:31,427 --> 00:24:36,253
seventy-six, folded in with a seed
catalog and the light bill. Harlan opened

306
00:24:36,253 --> 00:24:41,530
it standing at the mailbox, and his hands
were not steady, which surprised him more

307
00:24:41,530 --> 00:24:44,168
than it would have surprised anyone else.

308
00:24:44,168 --> 00:24:49,418
The numbers were typed and small. Organic
matter, which had tested at zero point

309
00:24:49,418 --> 00:24:54,536
six percent the year Annie's plan went
into the water, now read one point two.

310
00:24:54,536 --> 00:24:59,653
Doubled. Two and a half years, and the
ground had doubled its living fraction.

311
00:24:59,653 --> 00:25:04,903
In the margin, in blue ink, someone at
the lab had written a question: microbial

312
00:25:04,903 --> 00:25:10,087
activity unusually high for this county —
what exactly are you doing out there?

313
00:25:10,087 --> 00:25:14,939
Harlan read it twice, folded the page
along its creases, and looked a long

314
00:25:14,939 --> 00:25:18,328
moment at the ditches shining between the
corn rows.

315
00:25:18,328 --> 00:25:24,258
That same season, the farm cleared a
profit for the first time in six years.

316
00:25:24,258 --> 00:25:30,188
Not because the yield was anything
remarkable — it was decent, no more — but

317
00:25:30,188 --> 00:25:36,356
because the spending had quietly gone
away: no fertilizer bill, half the diesel

318
00:25:36,356 --> 00:25:42,207
for pumping, no rented spreader in the
spring. The account book balanced in

319
00:25:42,207 --> 00:25:45,528
black ink so thin it looked like a
mistake.

320
00:25:45,528 --> 00:25:50,887
And the fish had become the second crop.
Saturday mornings they set up at the

321
00:25:50,887 --> 00:25:56,316
county market with a cooler of cleaned
tilapia on ice, firm and white-fleshed,

322
00:25:56,316 --> 00:26:01,674
and by ten the cooler was empty. Eli
weighed, wrapped, and counted change out

323
00:26:01,674 --> 00:26:07,245
of a cigar box that had done sadder work
in its time. Nobody at the market asked

324
00:26:07,245 --> 00:26:10,488
about the box, and he would not have told
them.

325
00:26:10,488 --> 00:26:15,764
When they got home the second Saturday,
Eli took the soil report off the counter

326
00:26:15,764 --> 00:26:20,974
and taped it to the kitchen wall beside
his mother's aquarium — low, at the eye

327
00:26:20,974 --> 00:26:26,250
height of a boy of seven, where a person
feeding fish every morning would see it

328
00:26:26,250 --> 00:26:31,660
without ever having to look up. [SOFTER]
Harlan left it exactly there. Annie would

329
00:26:31,660 --> 00:26:36,669
have read that margin note out loud at
supper, twice, and then framed it. He

330
00:26:36,669 --> 00:26:40,008
knew that the way he knew the smell of
rain coming.

331
00:26:40,008 --> 00:26:45,716
A number typed on a lab report travels no
farther than the man who reads it. A

332
00:26:45,716 --> 00:26:51,722
number chalked on the board at the grain
elevator travels every road in the county

333
00:26:51,722 --> 00:26:54,168
— and weighing season was coming.

334
00:26:54,168 --> 00:27:00,089
The drought did not arrive in the summer
of nineteen seventy-seven so much as it

335
00:27:00,089 --> 00:27:05,635
stopped pretending to leave. It had
settled over southwest Georgia the year

336
00:27:05,635 --> 00:27:10,957
before and stayed, and by July the
federal men had declared the county a

337
00:27:10,957 --> 00:27:16,953
disaster area, and the sky held the pale,
scoured blue of an old enamel basin. On

338
00:27:16,953 --> 00:27:22,874
the neighboring farms, ground that had
been fed from a sack for twenty years had

339
00:27:22,874 --> 00:27:28,795
gone salty and tired, crusted hard as a
biscuit left out overnight, and when the

340
00:27:28,795 --> 00:27:34,716
pumps threw water across it, the water
beaded and slid and ran off into the road

341
00:27:34,716 --> 00:27:40,787
ditches the way rain runs off a tin roof.
Men ran those pumps day and night. Their

342
00:27:40,787 --> 00:27:46,408
corn curled anyway, the leaves rolling
inward like hands closing on nothing.

343
00:27:46,408 --> 00:27:52,457
Harlan's ground was dark. Three winters
of fish plowed under had left it soft and

344
00:27:52,457 --> 00:27:58,128
open, and a handful of it held together
in the palm and smelled faintly of a

345
00:27:58,128 --> 00:28:03,874
riverbank. When he watered, the field
drank, and kept what it drank. His corn

346
00:28:03,874 --> 00:28:04,328
stood.

347
00:28:04,328 --> 00:28:09,751
At the grain elevator that September,
with the dust of other men's short crops

348
00:28:09,751 --> 00:28:15,245
hanging in the scale-house light, the
county average went up on the chalkboard:

349
00:28:15,245 --> 00:28:20,457
forty-one bushels an acre. The scale man
weighed Harlan's loads, worked his

350
00:28:20,457 --> 00:28:25,317
figures on a pad, and chalked
eighty-eight beside the name Boone. Then

351
00:28:25,317 --> 00:28:30,318
he stepped back and checked his own
arithmetic twice. [PAUSE] The number

352
00:28:30,318 --> 00:28:30,811
stayed.

353
00:28:30,811 --> 00:28:36,534
Nobody laughed. The laughter of three
years did not stop so much as run out of

354
00:28:36,534 --> 00:28:42,406
air, the way a wind dies at dusk without
anyone marking the moment it went. Earl

355
00:28:42,406 --> 00:28:48,352
Dobbins stood at the scale window a long
time, hat in his hand, reading the board

356
00:28:48,352 --> 00:28:52,811
the way a man reads a letter he knows he
will have to answer.

357
00:28:52,811 --> 00:28:58,065
That fall, Eli — who had quit telling
boys at school what his daddy did, who

358
00:28:58,065 --> 00:29:03,600
had eaten certain lunches alone over it —
stood up at show-and-tell with a mason

359
00:29:03,600 --> 00:29:09,064
jar of ditch water and one fingerling
circling inside, and talked about tilapia

360
00:29:09,064 --> 00:29:14,529
until the bell rang. Nobody laughed there
either. Afterward a boy asked, almost

361
00:29:14,529 --> 00:29:17,611
shyly, if he could come out and see the
fish.

362
00:29:17,611 --> 00:29:18,331
Eighty-eight.

363
00:29:18,331 --> 00:29:23,927
In the spring of nineteen seventy-eight,
Dale Kessler's car came up the farm road

364
00:29:23,927 --> 00:29:29,173
again, slower now, easing over the ruts
like a man who had learned what they

365
00:29:29,173 --> 00:29:34,839
cost. Natural gas had gone dear, and the
price of fertilizer had climbed after it,

366
00:29:34,839 --> 00:29:39,876
and farmers drowning in borrowed money
were canceling orders across three

367
00:29:39,876 --> 00:29:45,332
counties. Kessler stepped out into the
red dust in shoes nobody had polished in

368
00:29:45,332 --> 00:29:50,648
a long while, and there were lines around
his eyes that had not been there in

369
00:29:50,648 --> 00:29:56,244
nineteen seventy-four, when he had stood
in that same dust and said, "Think about

370
00:29:56,244 --> 00:30:00,091
the boy." Even the chrome on his bumper
had gone cloudy.

371
00:30:00,091 --> 00:30:05,513
Mr. Pruitt was already there, come out on
extension business he never quite named.

372
00:30:05,513 --> 00:30:10,800
He held his clipboard against his chest
with both hands, the way a man holds his

373
00:30:10,800 --> 00:30:16,155
hat at a funeral. "I found my notes from
that county meeting," he said. "The ones

374
00:30:16,155 --> 00:30:21,175
I read out loud. I owe you an apology,
Mr. Boone." The words came out of him

375
00:30:21,175 --> 00:30:23,451
gray, like ash off a burnt letter.

376
00:30:23,451 --> 00:30:30,005
Harlan let a moment pass. Then both men
asked, in different words that came down

377
00:30:30,005 --> 00:30:32,411
to the same single word: how.

378
00:30:32,411 --> 00:30:38,580
He did not gloat. He walked them the
length of the main ditch instead — the

379
00:30:38,580 --> 00:30:44,999
water moving, olive-backed fish turning
under the surface, the culvert screens

380
00:30:44,999 --> 00:30:51,585
furred with green, the sump pond warm and
low and busy. In the kitchen he opened

381
00:30:51,585 --> 00:30:58,004
the ledger on the table and turned it
toward them, and what he showed them was

382
00:30:58,004 --> 00:31:04,507
not what he had earned but what he had
never bought: no nitrogen since nineteen

383
00:31:04,507 --> 00:31:10,759
seventy-four, no herbicide in two years,
the debt column thin as fence wire.

384
00:31:10,759 --> 00:31:16,011
Pruitt ran a finger down the page twice
and said nothing at all.

385
00:31:16,011 --> 00:31:20,726
Ray arrived while they stood there,
backing his truck to the ditch with a

386
00:31:20,726 --> 00:31:25,768
tank of fingerlings sloshing. He looked
Pruitt up and down once. "Hatchery men

387
00:31:25,768 --> 00:31:30,875
from four counties have been calling this
man for advice," he said, "since back

388
00:31:30,875 --> 00:31:34,411
when this county was still getting its
laughing done.".

389
00:31:34,411 --> 00:31:39,297
Kessler waited until the others had gone.
Then he laid a folder on the kitchen

390
00:31:39,297 --> 00:31:43,611
table, square in front of Harlan, and
smoothed it flat with one hand.

391
00:31:43,611 --> 00:31:49,439
Kessler read it out loud, because that
was still his gift — making numbers sound

392
00:31:49,439 --> 00:31:55,192
like weather coming. A license. The Boone
system, packaged: starter fish, pumps

393
00:31:55,192 --> 00:32:00,872
sized and branded, a printed program with
Harlan's name across the cover, sold

394
00:32:00,872 --> 00:32:06,405
statewide through the same dealers who
had once sold the sacks. Royalties on

395
00:32:06,405 --> 00:32:11,790
every unit moved. He said the figure
twice, and the second time he said it

396
00:32:11,790 --> 00:32:17,248
slowly, and it was more money than the
farm had earned in its whole hundred

397
00:32:17,248 --> 00:32:17,691
years.

398
00:32:17,691 --> 00:32:22,422
Behind them, on the counter, Annie's
thirty-gallon aquarium hummed. The

399
00:32:22,422 --> 00:32:27,694
evening light came through it and laid a
small trembling square of green on the

400
00:32:27,694 --> 00:32:32,967
wall, next to the soil report Eli had
taped there, and the water inside went on

401
00:32:32,967 --> 00:32:38,171
turning past the chipped front corner the
way it had turned for fifteen years.

402
00:32:38,171 --> 00:32:40,571
Harlan looked at the folder a long time.

403
00:32:40,571 --> 00:32:46,313
Eli stood in the doorway in his socks,
nine years old that spring, listening the

404
00:32:46,313 --> 00:32:51,692
way children listen, with the whole body.
"Mom gave her tomatoes away every

405
00:32:51,692 --> 00:32:54,091
summer," he said. "All of them.".

406
00:32:54,091 --> 00:33:00,973
[SOFTER] Harlan closed the folder. "I did
not invent anything," he said. "I married

407
00:33:00,973 --> 00:33:07,771
a woman who kept fish, and after she was
gone I finally paid attention. You cannot

408
00:33:07,771 --> 00:33:13,646
sell a man his own listening." He laid
his hand flat on the folder, not

409
00:33:13,646 --> 00:33:19,940
unkindly. "And the day you put a price
sticker on the live part of this, the

410
00:33:19,940 --> 00:33:21,451
live part quits.".

411
00:33:21,451 --> 00:33:25,921
Kessler started to answer. Harlan lifted
two fingers off the table, and he

412
00:33:25,921 --> 00:33:26,411
stopped.

413
00:33:26,411 --> 00:33:28,971
"But I will tell you what I mean to do.".

414
00:33:28,971 --> 00:33:33,601
That same spring he opened the farm —
every Sunday afternoon, free, to any

415
00:33:33,601 --> 00:33:38,547
farmer who cared to walk the ditches and
ask questions. The first calls he made

416
00:33:38,547 --> 00:33:43,304
himself, in the evening, in the flat
voice he used for ordering seed, to the

417
00:33:43,304 --> 00:33:46,411
men who had laughed loudest at the county
meeting.

418
00:33:46,411 --> 00:33:52,161
Kessler drove away without a signature,
but with directions for Sunday. He came,

419
00:33:52,161 --> 00:33:58,130
too, in a plaid shirt, dusty to the knee,
standing at the back of the crowd. "Never

420
00:33:58,130 --> 00:34:03,371
once sold anything this good," he said,
quietly, to nobody in particular.

421
00:34:03,371 --> 00:34:08,745
The county had spent years waiting to see
what Harlan Boone was building, and it

422
00:34:08,745 --> 00:34:14,050
had guessed a product. It guessed wrong.
What he had put into that ground was a

423
00:34:14,050 --> 00:34:19,424
pulse — water moving through the farm's
veins like blood through a living body —

424
00:34:19,424 --> 00:34:24,661
and a pulse was not a thing a man could
bottle. It could only be passed along.

425
00:34:24,661 --> 00:34:29,559
Hand to hand, the way it had been passed
to him, out of a schoolteacher's

426
00:34:29,559 --> 00:34:30,171
aquarium.

427
00:34:30,171 --> 00:34:35,618
The eighties came in quietly. On Sunday
afternoons the pickup trucks parked nose

428
00:34:35,618 --> 00:34:40,583
to tail along the ditch road, a dozen
some weeks, men from three counties

429
00:34:40,583 --> 00:34:45,547
walking the banks with their hands
clasped behind them like visitors in a

430
00:34:45,547 --> 00:34:50,995
museum, leaning down to watch the fish
ride the current. Folks stopped bothering

431
00:34:50,995 --> 00:34:56,373
with the road's real name. They called it
Fish Road, and after a while the name

432
00:34:56,373 --> 00:34:59,131
found its way onto mailboxes and stayed.

433
00:34:59,131 --> 00:35:05,104
Earl Dobbins cut ditches of his own that
first spring and let Harlan talk him

434
00:35:05,104 --> 00:35:10,212
through the screens and the pump. By
nineteen eighty his water ran

435
00:35:10,212 --> 00:35:16,656
green-tinted and alive, and his corn came
in second-best in the county, and he told

436
00:35:16,656 --> 00:35:21,371
anybody who asked that second place had
never tasted so good.

437
00:35:21,371 --> 00:35:26,121
Each April, Eli waded the headgates in
rubber boots to turn the new generation

438
00:35:26,121 --> 00:35:30,933
loose from the sump pond. He was twelve
now, tall as his father's shoulder, and

439
00:35:30,933 --> 00:35:35,621
he went about it with the unhurried
gravity of a boy serving at an altar, the

440
00:35:35,621 --> 00:35:38,891
cold water pressing the rubber flat
against his shins.

441
00:35:38,891 --> 00:35:44,548
In the kitchen, Annie's aquarium hummed
on the counter the way it always had. New

442
00:35:44,548 --> 00:35:49,851
fish circled past the chipped front
corner; the soil report hung yellowed on

443
00:35:49,851 --> 00:35:55,296
the wall beside it. General the Second,
fat and entirely without shame, bumped

444
00:35:55,296 --> 00:36:00,457
the glass whenever anyone crossed the
room carrying anything that might be

445
00:36:00,457 --> 00:36:00,811
food.

446
00:36:00,811 --> 00:36:06,604
[SLOWER] One morning in the first gray
light, Harlan stood at the kitchen window

447
00:36:06,604 --> 00:36:12,178
with his coffee and watched his son move
along the main ditch, the boy's hand

448
00:36:12,178 --> 00:36:18,191
swinging wide, feed scattering across the
moving water, the surface breaking into a

449
00:36:18,191 --> 00:36:20,171
hundred small silver rings.

450
00:36:20,171 --> 00:36:25,654
The men with the degrees had looked at
that farm and seen a factory run out of

451
00:36:25,654 --> 00:36:31,208
fuel. A widower who had listened to his
wife's fish tank looked at it and saw a

452
00:36:31,208 --> 00:36:36,905
body that had stopped breathing. [WEIGHT]
And the distance between those two ways

453
00:36:36,905 --> 00:36:42,103
of seeing was the whole distance —
between a farm that died owing money to

454
00:36:42,103 --> 00:36:46,091
men in polished shoes, and a farm that
came back to life.

455
00:36:46,091 --> 00:36:50,491
Out along the rows, in the ditches, the
water kept moving.

